by ro0NL at 2016-08-08T13:42:24Z

@sstok

> Moet en moeten klinkt erg dwingend, mag niet klinkt wat vriendelijker.

This is about `should` vs `must`, where `must` is used in several dutch translations currently, ie
- `This value _should not_ be blank.` = `Deze waarde _mag niet_ leeg zijn` (OK)
- `This value _should_ be null.` = `Deze waarde _moet_ null zijn.` (Reads as `This value _must_ be null.`)

Shall we change this right now? Sstok's point is `mag niet` (ie `should not`) reads more friendly, which is true. In english you can compare this to `may not`.

edit: Hehe, this is perhaps hard to explain but it only counts when negated (ie `should not`). The 2nd example is also OK. `must` and `should` can both be  translated to `moet` in dutch. My bad.

> 'kon niet gevonden worden' is meer gebruikelijk dan 'kon niet worden gevonden'.

(Dutch) Zeker?, ik vind beide nu duidelijk (worden geupload en worden gevonden). Geen idee of hier grammatica regels bij komen kijken eigenlijk :sweat_smile: google translate vertaald het als "worden gevonden" in ieder geval, zonder verdere suggesties. :confused:

> Vertalingen hoeven niet letterlijk te worden overgenomen, zolang als de oorspronkelijke bedoeling duidelijk is.

This is about `This value is not valid.` meaning the same as `This value is invalid`. Which both can be separately translated in dutch. Sstok's point is it basically doesnt matter to much how you translate this (it means the same). Ie. `This value is invalid` could be translated as `... is ongeldig` (literally `... is invalid`) or `... is niet geldig` (literally `... is not valid`).

Currently i "corrected" this for `This value should be false.`. I tend to agree with sstok (for pragmatic reasons) but still think we should do a "correct" translation when possible (ie not changing syntax/words to much). Especially since these are mostly translations with 1-2 sentences... fully agree with sstok when it comes to translating complete paragraphs.

